tags.name: Addington Point
tags.note: Addington Point, officially adopted 3 May 1951, was named by Captain Richards in 1859–60, presumably for Henry Addington (1757–1844), British Prime Minister 1801–04 and later Viscount Sidmouth. Recorded on Admiralty charts and BC Geological Survey maps.

tags.name: Brockton Point
tags.note: Brockton Point, adopted 7 Dec 1937, was named in 1859 by Captain Richards, RN, after Francis Brockton, Chief Engineer on HM surveying vessel Plumper. Brockton reportedly discovered coal in nearby Coal Harbour while surveying what is now Stanley Park.

tags.description: Used for pulling logs from the water

tags.name: Douglas Island
tags.note: Douglas Island, officially adopted 1936, was named for HBC Chief Factor James Douglas (1803–1877), founder of Victoria and BC governor. Previously mislabeled “Manson Island” on Admiralty charts; all island lots were purchased by Douglas in 1859.

tags.name: Barnston Island
tags.note: Barnston Island, named for George Barnston, a Hudson’s Bay Company clerk who joined James McMillan’s 1827 expedition to establish Fort Langley. Barnston had formerly worked with the Northwest Company before the HBC merger.
